The paper deals with the complexity of solving optimization problems on quantum circuits of small treewidth, which is a topic closely related to computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of treewidth as a parameter also suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper specifically focuses on the quantum setting, which falls under quantum computing (cs.QC). The use of probability and information theory in the analysis of the algorithms suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper also discusses the power of quantum witnesses compared to classical witnesses, which is a topic related to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
